Conditions on Approval:
The Approved Provider must engage an appropriate expert, such as a person/entity holding a Queensland Building and Construction Commission licence in Emergency Procedures, a fire safety advisor or fire safety engineer, to observe and report on one full rehearsal at least annually by the end of January. A copy of the annual evacuation outcome report, including any recommendations for actioning is to be supplied to the Regional Office of the Regulatory Authority in which the service is located within 7 days upon receipt of the report by the Approved Provider from the licensed organisation. The service is approved to provide education and care to children from birth up to and including over preschool age. The service is not approved to provide education and care to school children. The mirrors installed at the service are constantly maintained and operational to ensure the facilitation of supervision of children at all times they are being educated and cared for at the service, having regard to the need to maintain the rights and dignity of the children as required under regulation 115 of the Education and Care Services National Regulations. The service is approved to provide education and care to children up to 2 years of age on the first floor of the service only. The approved provider must ensure that no outdoor play equipment is placed within one metre of the perimeter fencing in the roof top outdoor play area. The approved provider must not provide education and care to more than 16 non-ambulant infants at any one time. The approved provider must ensure that a ratio of 1 staff member to 2 non-ambulant infants is maintained within the service at all times education and care is provided to non-ambulant infants, to assist in the safe evacuation of these children from the service during regular rehearsals and any actual emergency. Staff who are responsible for evacuating non-ambulant infants are not to be responsible for evacuating any other children, other than children who are 3-5 years old. Staff who are responsible for evacuating children aged 2-3 years old are not to be responsible for evacuating any other children. The approved provider must ensure that at any time education and care is provided to children, the following number of staff must be present, regardless of any required educator to child ratios:
a.	within the level 2 children’s indoor space, a minimum of 4 educators must be present;
b.	in the level 3 playground, a minimum of 4 educators must be present; and
c.	in the level 4 playground, a minimum of 3 educators must be present. It is a condition of the service waiver that the Approved Provider must ensure that a supervision plan is in place to ensure that the blind spots on all levels are adequately supervised. The Approved Provider must ensure that all staff are trained in relation to the supervision plan and that the plan is followed by all staff at all times that children are being educated and cared for. It is a condition of the service waiver that the Approved Provider must ensure that convex mirrors are installed and maintained at all times. The mirrors must be positioned to ensure that adequate supervision of the corners and blind spots on throughout the service can be maintained. It is a condition of the service waiver that the Approved Provider must ensure that a minimum ratio of 1:9 educators to children is maintained on level 2 of the service in relation to children aged 3-5 years at all times that children are being educated and cared for. It is a condition of the service waiver that the Approved Provider must ensure that a supervising educator is stationed outside the nappy change and toilet area on level 2 at all times that toileting and nappy changes are taking place. In relation to the level 3 play space, it is a condition of the service waiver that the Approved Provider must ensure the following minimum ratios are maintained at all times that children are being educated and cared for:
a.	1:9 educators to children in relation to children aged 3-5; and
b.	1:4 educators to children in relation to children aged 2-3. In relation to the level 4 play space, it is a condition of the service waiver that the Approved Provider must ensure the following minimum ratios are maintained at all times that children are being educated and cared for:
a.	1:9 educators to children in relation to children aged 3-5; and
b.	1:4 educators to children in relation to children aged 2-3.

Conditions on Approval:
This service is approved to provide education and care to children from 15 months up to and including school children. The Approved Provider must keep separate the two types of transportation of children it conducts. Particularly, the Approved Provider must not transport, on the same vehicle at the same time:

a.	Children who are being transported to or from the service premises; and

b.	Children who are being transported directly between:

i.	Home;

ii.	School; or

iii.	An excursion destination.
 The Approved Provider must, on request from the Regulatory Authority, provide the following documents within 14 days of receiving that request:

a.	Commonwealth data submission for a one week period;
b.	Bus rolls for a one week period; and
c.	Attendance record under regulation 158 of the National Regulations for a one week period.
 At all times that children are being transported, the Approved Provider must ensure that there is a minimum of two appropriately qualified paid or unpaid staff members on the vehicle (which may include work experience students or other volunteers that are on the books and records, and under the direct supervision and direction of the Approved Provider), with at least one paid or unpaid staff member acting solely in a supervisory capacity. The minimum qualification for paid or unpaid staff members on the vehicle are that:

a.	They all hold a current blue card;
b.	They are all trained in the transportation policy and procedure and participate in regular rehearsals of the procedure;
c.	Either the driver or the supervisor (or both) hold a current approved first aid qualification; and
d.	Either the driver or the supervisor (or both) have had current approved anaphylaxis management training and current approved asthma management training.
 The Approved Provider must ensure that all staff are inducted in the transportation policy and procedure, and have completed practical training. Practical training must also occur following any updates to the transportation policy and procedure. The Approved Provider must ensure that a record of the training is kept at the Service for inspection by an Authorised Officer. The Approved Provider must ensure the transportation policy and procedure is rehearsed at least quarterly and must ensure that a record of these rehearsals is kept available for inspection at the Service by Authorised Officers.

This is to ensure the facilitation of adequate supervision of children at all times they are being educated and cared for at the service, having regard to the need to maintain the rights and dignity of the children, as required under regulation 115 of the Education and Care Services National Regulations. The approved provider must ensure that no outdoor play equipment or natural vegetation is placed within one metre of the perimeter fencing of any children's outdoor play space. As part of the requirement to conduct three (3) monthly emergency and evacuation procedures rehearsals in accordance with regulation 97(3) of the Education and Care Services National Regulations the approved provider must, from the date of the initial service approval, engage an appropriate expert in emergency procedures, a fire safety advisor or fire safety engineer to observe and report on one rehearsal (including any proposed actions to improve evacuation procedures) within the first three months of the service’s operation, and then at least annually thereafter. A copy of the initial (within three (3) months) and the annual evacuation outcome report, including any recommendations for actioning, is to be supplied to the Regional Office of the Regulatory Authority in which the service is located within seven (7) days upon receipt of the report by the approved provider.  An adequate amount of healthy live plants in a variety of species and sizes is maintained at all times, in the children’s outdoor play areas across all levels of the service premises, ensuring children are afforded opportunities to explore and experience the features of a natural environment as required under regulation 113 of the Education and Care Services National Regulations. It is a condition of the service waiver that the approved provider must utilise 200.5 m² of covered space in the play areas, located on the upper ground and lower ground levels, to satisfy part of the unencumbered outdoor space requirements.

It is a condition of Building 2 (levels 3, 4 and 5) – In the Wild that:
- natural vegetation in the planter boxes provided in the ‘enclosed’ outdoor area must be maintained at all times which is equivalent of 4% of the minimum outdoor play space required for this area in at least the location outlined in the application; and

- programming must provide opportunities for children to participate in activities which reflect on nature; and
- the balustrades used on the three sides of the balcony must have no gaps or 'foot holds' at any height or if necessary, any gap must be positioned at a height of at least 1200mm from the floor; and  
- consideration must be given to the location of the planter boxes and timber box seats and ensure that they are positioned in a place that does not allow them to be used by children as a step to attempt to climb any perimeter balustrade. Planter boxes and plants are monitored regularly and unacceptable risks will be addressed immediately. This condition applies to Building 2 (level 3, 4 and 5) - In the Wild only. Fire stairs between level 4 and 5 in Building 2 – In the Wild are only to be used during an emergency evacuation process. This may include evacuation drills. This condition applies to Building 2 (level 3, 4 and 5) - In the Wild only. The Approved Provider must engage an appropriate expert, such as a person/entity holding a Queensland Building and Construction Commission licence in Emergency Procedures, a fire safety advisor or fire safety engineer, to observe and report on one full rehearsal at least annually by the end of May.
